1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3 dxc3 (3... d5 { A very nice "take-out" line to have in your back pocket. Black immediately strikes back, forcing a liquidation of center pawns and leading to an IQP structure in which Black's rapid development and active queen will grant us excellent, straightforward play. Should White respond correctly, this move does not afford us an objective advantage, but it is a great move to play in ultra-short time control games (such as in bullet) and, if caught unaware, White can absolutely slide into a miserable position in just a few short moves. Perhaps the biggest appeal of this line is that the lines are quite forcing, making it very easy to memorize in just a few short minutes. } 4. exd5 (4. Qxd4?! { A toothless move that merely leads to a slightly worse position for White. Black has myriad ways to respond, but the simplest is probably: } 4... Be6!? 5. exd5 (5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 Nc6 7. Bb5 dxe4 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxe4 O-O-O! 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Qxc6? Rd1+!! 12. Kxd1 Bb3+ $19) 5... Bxd5 6. c4 (6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Bb5 a6 8. Bxc6+ Bxc6 9. O-O Qxd4 10. Nxd4 Bd7 11. Re1+ Ne7 $15) 6... Qe7+! 7. Be3 Be6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Qd2 Rd8 $36)  (4. e5? { A staggering 130,000 or so games featured this move! } 4... dxc3 5. Nxc3 d4 6. Nb5 (6. Ne4 Qd5 7. Bd3 Nc6 { Of course, we do not rush to grab e5. } 8. Nf3 Bg4 9. O-O Nxe5 10. Qa4+ Bd7 11. Qd1 Nxd3 12. Qxd3 Bb5 13. Re1!? O-O-O! $19) 6... Nc6 7. Nf3 Bg4 8. Be2 Bb4+ 9. Kf1 d3! 10. Qxd3 Qxd3 11. Bxd3 O-O-O $19) 4... Qxd5 5. cxd4 (5. Nf3 Nc6 6. cxd4 Bb4+ { Transposes to the main line (5.cxd4 Nc6 6.Nf3 Bb4+). }) 5... Nc6 6. Nf3 (6. Nc3? Qxd4 7. Qe2+ Be6 8. Be3 Qd7 9. Rd1 Bd6 $17)  (6. Be3?! Bb4+ 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 O-O 10. Nf3 Qa5! 11. Qb3 Bg4 12. Be2 Nd5 13. Rc1 Rae8 $17) 6... Bb4+ { An important check, taking the sting out of Nc3. } 7. Nc3 (7. Bd2 Bg4 8. Bxb4 { Here, it is crucial not to automatically recapture on b4, which leads to unpleasant consequences after Qa4+. Instead, we throw in another capture, which changes