3 (6. Qb3 Qh4! $146 7. Bxf7+ (7. g3 Qf6 { Having induced a major weakening of White's kingside, the queen triumphantly returns to home base. White must now weaken the kingside even further. } 8. f4 (8. Bf4 Ne7 $17) 8... Qe7! { This is, undeniably, engine-like play, but the logic behind each of Black's last three moves should be amply clear! The queen aims at the e4 pawn, taking the sting out of the knight jump on d5. More importantly, the queen yields the right-of-way to the knight, which will now develop to its most active square. } 9. Nf3 Nf6 10. e5 Nbd7 11. Bd2 dxe5 12. O-O-O (12. fxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5+ 14. Ne2 O-O $19 { "heliaverdi"-"Iambertwp," Lichess (blitz) 2023. }) 12... e4 { There is nothing to fear, because Black is about to hide away on the kingside. } 13. Rhe1 O-O 14. Ng5 e3! { White's position collapses, e.g. } 15. Kb1 Nb6 16. Bd3 h6 17. Nf3 Bg4 $19)  (7. Qc2! { This practically unfindable move is the only way for White to limit the scope of Black's advantage. On Lichess, it has only been played ONCE (out of a total of more than 100 games, 79 of which featured the much more natural 7.g3). Abandoning the attack on f7 signifies that White is fully aware of the dangers involved in capturing on f7 and weakening the kingside with 7.g3. Black, however, is still very much in the driver's seat and a few precise moves will yield a slightly better position: } 7... Qg4! { Continuing to poke and prod at the kingside. } 8. f3 (8. g3 Ne7 9. h3 Qg6 10. Nf3 Nbc6 $17 { White has no compensation for the pawn. }) 8... Qh4+ 9. g3 Qd8 10. Nge2 (10. Qb3 Qd7 { Black's last five moves have been with the queen, and yet he is none the worse for wear! White's kingside is riddled with holes, and let's not forget that Black is up a pawn to begin with! } 11. Nge2 Nc6 12. Qc2 Ne5 $19) 10... Nf6 11. Bg5 { To my eyes, this is the most human response. } (11. Na4 { According to the engine, this is - once again - the only way to ensure that Black does not have a big advantage. If your opponent finds all of these moves, you can take your hat off...and still claim a better position after: } 11... Bb6 12. Nxb6 axb6 13. Nf4 O-O 14. Be3 Nc6 15. O-O Ne5 16. Bb3 Bd7 $15 { White has the bishop pair, but not too much else by way of compensation. Meanwhile, Black has long-term pressure on f3, as well as the idea of queenside expansion with ...Bb5 and ...c7-c5. }) 11... Nc6 12. Nd5 { There is nothing to fear: } 12... Ne5! 13. O-O-O (13. f4 Nf3+ 14. Kd1 Nxg5 15. fxg5 Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Qxg5 $19)  (13. Rf1 c6 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Bd2 Bh3 $19) 13... c6 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Bh6 b5 16. Bb3 Rg8! { Black's king is chilling in the center - the mass of pawns may appear ugly, but prevents White from developing any sort of attack in the center. In human terms, White is borderline lost - a single further inaccuracy will lead to immediate collapse. } 17. Rhf1 a5 18. a3 a4 19. Ba2 Qb6 { With the devastating twin threats of ...Bh3 and ...b4. White hasn't even gotten off the ground. }) 7... Kf8 8. g3 { By far the most natural move, although it exacerbates an already difficult position. } (8. Nd1 Qxe4+ 9. Ne2 (9. Kf1 Nf6) 9... Nf6 10. Bg5 Nbd7 11. Ne3 Bb4+ 12. Nc3 Nc5 $19 { "syria2008"-"thousand_sunny," Lichess (blitz) 2021. })  (8. Kd1 { Here, 8...Qxf2 allows a weird engine response (9.Bh5), after which the position remains unclear. Black should instead prioritize rapid development: } 8... Nc6! 9. Nf3 Qxf2 10. Bh5 { Now, this move is quite easy to parry: } 10... g6 { The chief difference is that with the inclusion of Nf3 and ...Nc6, White's bishop has no place to go! } 11. Qc4 Qxg2! 12. Rf1 Ke8 $19)  (8. Bxg8 Qxf2+ 9. Kd1 Rxg8 10. Nge2 Qxg2 11. Re1 Bf2 12. Nf4 Qf3+ 13. Re2 Nc6 14. Ncd5 Qxb3+ 15. axb3 Bg4 $19) 8... Qf6! 9. Bxg8 (9. Be3 { This has been played 10 times! } 9... Bxe3 10. fxe3 Qxf7 $19) 9... Qxf2+ 10. Kd1 Rxg8 11. Nge2 Nc6 12. Bd2 Qf3! { A very precise move, going after the rook. } 13. Kc2 (13. Re1 Nd4 $19) 13... Nb4+ 14. Qxb4 Bxb4 15. Rhf1 Qxf1 16. Rxf1+ Ke8 17. Nd5 Bxd2 18. Nxc7+ Kd8 19. Nxa8 Bg5 $19 { Black will easily trap the knight in the corner, either by means of ...b6-Bb7 or ...Bd7-c6 and ...Kd7. }) 6... Nf6 7. O-O (7. e5 { I forgot to include this move in the video - White immediately forces an endgame, but fails to acquire enough compensation for the pawn. } 7... dxe5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nxe5 (9. Bxf7 Nc6) 9... Re8 10. Bf4 Be6 11. O-O-O+ Kc8 12. Bxe6+ fxe6 $15) 7... O-O 8. Bg5 (8. Qb3 Nbd7 9. Bg5 c6) 8... Nbd7 9. Nd5 (9. Re1 c6 10. e5 (10. Na4 Bb4)  (10. Qc2 Ne5 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Rad1 Qe7 13. Ne2 Bxf2+) 10... Nxe5 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Rxe5 Bxf2+!) 9... c6 10. Nxf6+ Nxf6 11. Qc2 (11. e5 dxe5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Nxe5 Be6 $17) 11... h6 12. Bh4 d5 13. exd5 cxd5 14. Rad1 Qd6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Bxd5 Bb6 17. Rfe1 Bf5 $15 { Black has the bishop pair and a serious initiative. }) 4... cxb2 5. Bxb2 Nf6 6. e5 (6. Nc3 d5 7. exd5 (7. Nxd5 Nxd5 8. Bxd5 Bb4+ 9. Kf1 c6 10. Bxf7+ Kxf7 11. Qb3+ Be6 12. Qxb4 Qd3+ 13. Ne2 Rd8 14. Qxb7+ (14. Re1 Nd7) 14... Nd7 15. Qxc6 Rac8 $19) 7... Bd6 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Bg4 $15)  (6. Nf3 Bb4+ 7. Nc3 (7. Nbd2 O-O 8. O-O d6 9. Qc2 Nbd7 10. Rad1 Qe7 $17) 7... O-O 8. O-O Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Nxe4 10. Bb2 Nc6 11. Re1 Nf6 12. Ng5 d5 13. Bd3 Ng4 14. Nxh7 (14. Qd2 Qd6 15. g3 h6) 14... Qh4 $19)  (6. Qb3 d5 7. exd5 Bd6 8. Nf3 Qe7+ 9. Be2 O-O 10. Nc3 Bb4 11. O-O Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Qxe2 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Rfe1 Qa6 15. Nd4 Kh8 16. Re7 Nd7 17. Rae1 Ne5 $17)  (6. Nd2?! { A weird and toothless move, although it has been played over 30k times on Lichess! The simplest option is to give away one of our pawns in order to blast open the center and nip White's initiative in the bud. } 6... d5!? 7. exd5 Bd6 8. Ngf3 Qe7+ 9. Be2 Nxd5 10. O-O (10. Bxg7 Rg8 11. Bb2 Rxg2 $19) 10... Be6 11. Bxg7 Rg8 12. Bb2 Nc6 $17 { Black will castle queenside, with a monumental attack down the open d- and g-files. }) 6... Bb4+ 7. Nc3 { By far the most common move, and the one you are likely to face 90% of the time. It is crucial to remember Black's next move, which sets the center aflame. } (7. Kf1 d5 8. Bb5+ (8. exf6 dxc4 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. fxg7 Rg8 11. Nf3 Nd7 12. Ng5 Ke7 13. Nc3 Nf6 14. Re1+ Be6 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17. Rxe4 Rad8 18. g3 b5 19. Kg2 Bd2) 8... Nfd7 9. e6 fxe6 10. Bxg7 Kf7)  (7. Bc3 { This is the least intuitive of White's options (other than 7.Qd2, the analysis of which I will leave to the viewer), yet it is the only way to prevent a borderline lost position. Encouragingly, it has been played in only around 2.5 thousand games on Lichess (compared to a staggering 40,000 and 22,000 in Nc3 and Nd2, respectively). White uses the bishop trade to get his knight into better position, and restrict its vis-a-vis from accessing the e4-square. Here, it is important to refrain from automatically capturing on c3 (which would help White develop), and instead to maintain the tension with a very important resource. } 7... Qe7! (7... Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 { This is an interesting alternative, but I decided to refrain from reccommending it due to the complications which arise after: } 9. exf6 dxc4 10. fxg7 Rg8 11. Qf3 Rxg7 12. Nge2 { Black is objectively better, but the open king and the nasty prospect of White's rook coming to d1 makes the position rather unappetizing from a practical standpoint. }) 8. Qe2 (8. Nf3? { Almost as popular as 8.Qe2, yet this loses: } 8... Ne4! 9. Qb3 Nc6 10. O-O Nc5! 11. Qb2 Ne6 12. Nbd2 Bxc3 13. Qxc3 $19)  (8. a3?? Bxc3+ 9. Nxc3 Qxe5+ $19)  (8. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 9. Nd2 Ne4 10. Bxf7+ Kxf7 11. Qf3+ Ke7 12. Qxe4 Nc6 $17) 8... Ng8 { It may seem dreadfully risky to un-develop the knight, but White's develop advantage never grows to uncontrollable proportions. Crucially, we will re-develop the knight to h6, from where it can acccess the center through f5. The tension between the bishops on the queenside prevents White from easily accessing the d5-square with his knight. In order to keep Black's advantage at bay, White must play like a computer for the next 10 moves or so - and even then, Black is clearly better! } 9. Nf3 (9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. Nxc3 Nh6 11. Nd5 Qc5 12. Rc1 Qa5+! 13. Kf1 c6 (13... O-O?? 14. Nxc7! Qxc7 15. Bxf7+ $18) 14. Nc3 O-O 15. Nf3 Qxa3 $19) 9... Nh6 10. O-O O-O 11. Bxb4 (11. a3 Bxc3 12. Nxc3 Nc6 13. Nd5 Qd8 { Transposes to 11.Bxb4 Qxb4 12.a3 Qe7 13.Nc3 Nc6 14.Nd5 Qd8. }) 11... Qxb4 12. a3 Qe7 13. Nc3 Nc6 14. Nd5 (14. Rfe1 d6 15. Nd5 (15. exd6 Qxe2 16. Rxe2 cxd6 17. Ne4 Bg4! 18. Nxd6 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Nd4 20. Re4 Nxf3+ 21. Kg2 Nd2 $17) 15... Qd8 16. Rad1)  (14. Rae1 d6 $17) 14... Qd8 15. Rfe1 (15. Rad1 d6! 16. exd6 cxd6) 15... d6 16. Rad1 (16. exd6 cxd6 17. Rad1 (17. Ne7+ Nxe7 18. Qxe7 d5 19. Qxd8 Rxd8 20. Bxd5 Rb8 $17) 17... Be6) 16... Bg4 17. exd6 Qxd6 18. h3 (18. Nb6 Nd4 19. Rxd4 Qxb6 $17) 18... Bxf3 19. Qxf3 Rae8 20. Rxe8 Rxe8 21. Bb5 (21. Qb3 Ne5 22. Bf1 c6 $17) 21... Kf8 22. Nb4 (22. Bxc6 Qxc6 $19) 22... Nd4 23. Qxb7 g6 24. Nc2 (24. Bxe8 Ne2+ 25. Kh1 Qxd1+ 26. Kh2 Qg1#) 24... Nhf5 25. Rxd4 Nxd4 26. Bxe8 Nxc2 27. Bxf7! Kxf7 28. Qb3+ Kf6 29. Qxc2 Qxa3 30. Qc6+ (30. Qxc7 Qa1+ 31. Kh2 Qe5+ $19) 30... Qd6 $15)  (7. Nd2 { This is the second most common move. Like the more popular 7.Nc3, it essentially loses the game. We take the opportunity to counter-strike in the center, with a thematic shot that hits the bishop on c4 and instantly nips White's central play in the bud. } 7... d5! 8. exf6 (8. exd6 Qxd6 9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O Nc6 $19)  (8. Bb3?? { This mindless move has been played over a thousand times. } 8... Ne4 9. Nf3 Bg4 $19) 8... dxc4 9. fxg7 Rg8 { White's pawn on g7 may appear imposing, but its power is fully circumscribed by the rook, which cannot be chased away from g8 anytime soon. Black's 4 v 1 pawn mass on the queenside, coupled with the pressure on the d2 knight, spells instant doom for White's underdeveloped army. } 10. Rc1 Nc6 11. Rxc4 Bf5 12. Nf3 Qe7+ 13. Qe2 O-O-O 14. Qxe7 Bxe7 15. Rf4 Bg6 16. O-O Nb4 17. Ba1 Nd5 18. Ra4 f6 19. Rxa7 Kb8 20. Ra4 Rxg7 $19) 7... d5! { A very standard technique in a lot of 1.e4 e5 openings, such as the Scotch Gambit. Black opens up the dark-squared bishop, grabs control of the center, and counter-attacks White's LSB. } 8. exf6 (8. exd6? { Senseless. } 8... Qxd6 9. Qb3 Nc6! 10. Bxf7+ (10. Rd1 Qe7+ 11. Ne2 Na5 12. Qa4+ Bd7 13. Bb5 O-O-O! 14. Bxd7+ Nxd7 15. O-O Nb6 16. Qb5 Nac4 $19) 10... Kf8 11. Ne2 (11. Bc4 Na5 $19)  (11. Rd1 Qe7+ $19)  (11. Nf3 Qe7+ $19) 11... Na5 $19)  (8. e6) 8... Qxf6! { A very important follow-up. Taking the bishop immediately leads to a messy position. This, meanwhile, leads to dire straits for White. } 9. Qe2+ { The most popular move by far, and it loses instantly. } (9. Ne2 dxc4 10. O-O O-O 11. Nd5 (11. Rb1 Qh4 $19) 11... Qxb2 12. Rb1 Qe5 13. Nxb4 Bf5 14. Rc1 c5 $19)  (9. Bb5+ { The only move to avoid a completely losing position, although it has been virtually unplayed. } 9... c6 10. Ne2 cxb5 11. O-O Nc6 12. Rb1 (12. Nxd5 Qxb2 13. Nc7+ Ke7 14. Nxa8 Bg4 15. f3 Be6 16. Nc7 Rd8 $19) 12... O-O 13. Nxd5 Qh4 14. Nef4 (14. Nxb4 Nxb4 15. Ba3 a5 $17) 14... Bc5 15. Rc1 b6 $17) 9... Be6 10. Bxd5 (10. O-O-O Bxc3 11. Bxd5 Bxb2+ 12. Qxb2 Qxb2+ 13. Kxb2 Bxd5 14. Rxd5 Nd7 $19)  (10. Bb5+ c6 11. Rc1 d4! $19) 10... Bxc3+ 11. Bxc3 Qxc3+ $19 *


